#Is number prime or not

Logic-
1. If ğ‘›<=1, it's not prime.
2. If ğ‘› = 2, it's prime (the only even prime number).
3. If n is divisible by 2, it's not prime.

By Naive Method -

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

bool isPrime(int n) {
    // Edge cases
    if (n <= 1) return false;  // 0 and 1 are not prime numbers
    if (n == 2 || n == 3) return true;  // 2 and 3 are prime numbers

    // Check for factors from 2 to n-1
    for (int i = 2; i < n; ++i) {
        if (n % i == 0) return false;  // If divisible by any number other than 1 and itself
    }

    return true;  // No divisors found, so it is prime
}

int main() {
    int number;
    cout << "Enter a number: ";
    cin >> number;

    if (isPrime(number)) {
        cout << number << " is a prime number." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << number << " is not a prime number." << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

output - 
Enter a number: 5
5 is a prime number.
Enter a number: 6
6 is not a prime number.
